  \{\
    "title": "Holy Water",\
    "artist(s)": "We The Kingdom",\
    "suggested_male_key": "B",\
    "suggested_female_key": "D",\
    "tempo": "Upbeat",\
    "bpm": 73,\
    "themes": ["forgiveness", "freedom", "joy"],\
    "summary": "A joyful celebration of God\'92s mercy that likens forgiveness to soul-refreshing water. It invites the church to clap and sing about the freedom we find in Christ\'92s grace, responding with gratitude and praise.",\
    "theology": "\'93Holy Water\'94 emphasizes that, just as water cleanses, the blood of Jesus cleanses us from sin (1 John 1:7). It rejoices in the undeserved favor of God \'96 His mercy and kindness that lead us to repentance. The song teaches that forgiveness is a sweet gift, not to be taken for granted, and our proper response is heartfelt worship and thanksgiving to the One who set us free.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Psalm 51:7", "Ephesians 1:7", "1 John 1:7"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This high-energy song works well as an opener or closing praise. Encourage clapping and freedom in worship as you lead it. Musically, its folk-rock feel and memorable chorus engage the congregation quickly. Consider using it after a testimony or sermon on grace to reinforce the joy of salvation.",\
    "seo_title": "Holy Water \'96 We The Kingdom Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Holy Water\'94 by We The Kingdom is an upbeat worship song celebrating God\'92s cleansing mercy and forgiveness. Discover its joyful themes of freedom and grace, scriptural foundations, and tips for leading it in congregational worship."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Egypt",\
    "artist(s)": "Bethel Music (Cory Asbury)",\
    "suggested_male_key": "G",\
    "suggested_female_key": "C",\
    "tempo": "Moderate",\
    "bpm": 75,\
    "themes": ["deliverance", "thanksgiving", "God\'92s power"],\
    "summary": "This song joyfully recounts God\'92s deliverance of His people, comparing our personal salvation to the Exodus from Egypt. It leads the congregation in thanking God for victory and freedom, stirring faith that the God who rescued in the past still fights for us today.",\
    "theology": "\'93Egypt\'94 draws on the biblical Exodus narrative (Exodus 14), celebrating God as our mighty Deliverer. The lyrics highlight God\'92s faithful guidance, portraying salvation as being led out of bondage into freedom. It affirms that it\'92s God\'92s hand alone that defeats our enemy and brings us into a promised inheritance. Theologically, it reminds worshippers that the same God who parted the Red Sea is present and powerful to save us from sin and fear.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Exodus 14:13-14", "Deuteronomy 6:21", "Colossians 1:13"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Use \'93Egypt\'94 as an energetic declaration of God\'92s saving power \'96 it fits well after testimonies of God\'92s faithfulness or messages on freedom. Encourage the congregation to reflect on their own \'91Egypt\'92 moments where God brought deliverance. The song builds dynamically; consider having a choir or multiple vocalists join in on the bridge (\'93You stepped into my Egypt\'94) to elevate the celebration as you lead into the final chorus.",\
    "seo_title": "Egypt \'96 Bethel Music Deliverance Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Egypt\'94 by Bethel Music is a powerful worship song about God\'92s deliverance, likening personal salvation to the Exodus story. Explore its theme of freedom from bondage, biblical foundation, and suggestions for leading this song in church."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "New Wine",\
    "artist(s)": "Hillsong Worship",\
    "suggested_male_key": "G",\
    "suggested_female_key": "Bb",\
    "tempo": "Slow",\
    "bpm": 70,\
    "themes": ["surrender", "renewal", "Holy Spirit"],\
    "summary": "A reflective song of surrender that asks God to bring forth new growth and new anointing in our lives. It uses the image of pressing grapes into new wine to symbolize how God can use seasons of hardship to produce something valuable and new in us as we yield to Him.",\
    "theology": "\'93New Wine\'94 is rooted in the biblical concept that God brings renewal through surrender (Luke 5:37-38). The lyrics acknowledge that in Christ our lives are a living sacrifice \'96 as we lay down our old fire and old ways, God\'92s Spirit fills us with new power and purpose. This song\'92s theology centers on trust in God\'92s process of transformation; even in crushing or pressing seasons, He is working for our good and His glory (2 Corinthians 4:17). It\'92s a prayer for the Holy Spirit to form Christlikeness within us as we submit to His will.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Luke 5:37-39", "Romans 12:1-2", "2 Corinthians 4:17"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "\'93New Wine\'94 works well in response to a sermon about trust or during times of dedication and prayer. Musically, start gently to create a prayerful atmosphere. Encourage the congregation to make the words a personal prayer of surrender \'96 perhaps invite them to open their hands or kneel as a sign of yielding to God\'92s refining work. Flowing into a time of prayer or a song on the Holy Spirit after \'93New Wine\'94 can deepen the moment of commitment.",\
    "seo_title": "New Wine \'96 Hillsong Worship Song of Surrender",\
    "meta_description": "\'93New Wine\'94 by Hillsong Worship is a heartfelt song of surrender and renewal through the Holy Spirit. Learn about its message of transformation in trials, scriptural inspirations, and guidance for effectively leading this reflective worship song."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "All Hail King Jesus",\
    "artist(s)": "Jeremy Riddle",\
    "suggested_male_key": "C",\
    "suggested_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo": "Slow",\
    "bpm": 74,\
    "themes": ["Jesus\'92 lordship", "worship", "resurrection"],\
    "summary": "A reverent anthem that exalts the crucified and risen Christ as King of all. It carries the church through the Crucifixion scene into victorious resurrection praise, inviting everyone to bow in awe and proclaim the majesty of Jesus.",\
    "theology": "\'93All Hail King Jesus\'94 proclaims core gospel truths: Jesus\'92 death on the cross, His resurrection, and His supreme lordship (Philippians 2:8-11). The song\'92s theology is doxological \'96 it calls worshippers to join heaven in honoring Christ. Each verse and chorus acknowledges that Jesus has no equal and that every knee bows to Him. It emphasizes that through the cross and empty tomb, Christ earned the title King of Kings, and our response is unreserved worship and surrender to His reign.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Philippians 2:8-11", "Revelation 5:13", "Revelation 19:16"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Consider using this song during Easter season or any service focused on the cross and resurrection. It begins reflective and builds to a powerful declaration \'96 plan your band dynamics accordingly (start quietly, then swell with each section). Encourage the congregation to physically respond (lifting hands or bowing hearts) when singing \'93all hail King Jesus,\'94 helping them internalize the act of reverence. It can segue beautifully into a time of communion or any moment of exalting Christ\'92s victory.",\
    "seo_title": "All Hail King Jesus \'96 Jeremy Riddle Worship Anthem",\
    "meta_description": "\'93All Hail King Jesus\'94 by Jeremy Riddle is a worship anthem exalting Christ\'92s death and resurrection victory. Delve into its Christ-centered lyrics, biblical foundations of Jesus\'92 lordship, and tips for leading this powerful song in congregational worship."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Make Room",\
    "artist(s)": "Community Music",\
    "suggested_male_key": "F",\
    "suggested_female_key": "G",\
    "tempo": "Medium",\
    "bpm": 61,\
    "themes": ["surrender", "Jesus\'92 lordship", "devotion"],\
    "summary": "A gentle, prayerful song that declares our willingness to yield everything to Jesus. It repeatedly invites God to \'93have His way\'94 in us, encouraging the congregation to set aside personal agendas and wholeheartedly make room for Christ to move in their lives.",\
    "theology": "\'93Make Room\'94 emphasizes the lordship of Christ and the call to surrender (Luke 9:23). Theologically, it acknowledges that Jesus must increase as we decrease (John 3:30). The lyrics express repentance from selfish priorities and a desire for God to rearrange our hearts and lives according to His will. By singing \'93whatever You want to,\'94 the church prays a risky and biblical prayer of submission, trusting that God\'92s plans and ways are higher and better (Isaiah 55:8-9). It reinforces that worship is not just song, but yielded obedience to Jesus.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Luke 9:23", "John 3:30", "Romans 12:1"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song is effective just before a sermon or during response times, as it helps prepare hearts to receive God\'92s word. Keep the instrumentation simple and intimate to foster a personal prayer atmosphere. You might encourage the congregation to close their eyes or lift hands in an open posture as they sing \'93I will make room for You.\'94 If your team has both male and female vocalists, consider trading lines or harmonizing on the bridge (\'93Shake up the ground of all my tradition\'85\'94) to represent the unity in surrender among the whole church.",\
    "seo_title": "Make Room \'96 Community Music Worship Song of Surrender",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Make Room\'94 by Community Music is a reflective worship song about yielding our lives to Jesus\'92 will. Learn about its focus on surrender and devotion, the biblical themes it reflects, and practical advice for leading this song in a worship service."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Canvas and Clay",\
    "artist(s)": "Pat Barrett",\
    "suggested_male_key": "A",\
    "suggested_female_key": "D",\
    "tempo": "Medium",\
    "bpm": 70,\
    "themes": ["God\'92s sovereignty", "purpose", "identity in Christ"],\
    "summary": "This song is a reassuring meditation on how God, as the Master Artist, is shaping our lives with intention. It reminds the church that we are lovingly formed like clay in His hands \'96 never a mistake \'96 and that He works all things, even trials, for our good and His glory.",\
    "theology": "\'93Canvas and Clay\'94 draws from the truth that God is the Potter and we are the clay (Isaiah 64:8). Its theology is grounded in Romans 8:28, affirming that God uses every part of our story \'96 the light and dark strokes \'96 to create something beautiful. The song celebrates our identity as God\'92s workmanship (Ephesians 2:10), dispelling fear or insecurity by declaring \'93I know nothing has been wasted.\'94 It highlights God\'92s sovereignty and benevolent design in our lives, teaching that He forms each person with purpose and care.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Isaiah 64:8", "Romans 8:28", "Ephesians 2:10"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Introduce this song when your community needs encouragement about God\'92s purpose in difficult seasons. It works well after testimonies or sermons on trusting God\'92s plan. In leading, take time between verses or during a musical break to encourage the congregation with a brief exhortation: for example, remind them that God is at work in unseen ways. Musically, maintain a steady, warm dynamic \'96 too much intensity could overshadow the comforting message. Ending the song quietly on the final line \'93You\'92re not finished with me\'94 can create a powerful moment of reflection and trust.",\
    "seo_title": "Canvas and Clay \'96 Pat Barrett Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Canvas and Clay\'94 by Pat Barrett is a comforting worship song about God\'92s intentional design for our lives. Explore its themes of divine artistry and purpose, scriptural roots, and get practical tips for leading this song in your worship service."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Too Good To Not Believe",\
    "artist(s)": "Bethel Music (Brandon Lake)",\
    "suggested_male_key": "Bb",\
    "suggested_female_key": "Eb",\
    "tempo": "Medium",\
    "bpm": 72,\
    "themes": ["faith", "miracles", "God\'92s power"],\
    "summary": "A testimony-driven song declaring that after all we\'92ve seen God do, we cannot doubt His power and goodness. It builds the congregation\'92s faith to believe for miracles and proclaims that Jesus is still doing the impossible today \'96 too good not to trust.",\
    "theology": "\'93Too Good To Not Believe\'94 stands on the biblical truth that Jesus Christ is the same yesterday, today, and forever (Hebrews 13:8). The song\'92s theology recounts God\'92s miraculous deeds (healing, deliverance, salvation) much like the Psalms remember Israel\'92s history. It spurs on faith by professing that skepticism has no ground when faced with God\'92s evident goodness (Psalm 77:11-14). By listing miracles, it aligns with the idea that signs and wonders bear witness to the Gospel (Acts 14:3). Ultimately, it centers on Jesus\'92 power and goodness, urging believers to trust Him boldly.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Psalm 77:11-14", "Jeremiah 32:17", "Hebrews 13:8"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Use this song when encouraging your church to pray for healing or to strengthen faith in a powerful God. It works well after sharing testimonies of God\'92s intervention. As you lead, be genuinely expressive \'96 the song is a proclamation, so lead with conviction. Instrumentally, you can start subdued and let it build as the lyrics recount miracles, peaking at the declaration \'93Too good to not believe.\'94 Consider having a few people prepared to briefly share one-line testimonies in the instrumental break, which can amplify the impact before going back into a final chorus.",\
    "seo_title": "Too Good To Not Believe \'96 Bethel Music Song of Faith",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Too Good To Not Believe\'94 by Brandon Lake (Bethel Music) is a faith-filled worship song celebrating God\'92s miraculous power. Find out how it affirms Jesus\'92 ongoing work, the biblical miracles it references, and how to inspire faith when leading this song."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Jireh",\
    "artist(s)": "Elevation Worship & Maverick City Music",\
    "suggested_male_key": "C",\
    "suggested_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo": "Medium",\
    "bpm": 70,\
    "themes": ["God\'92s provision", "contentment", "faith"],\
    "summary": "A soulful worship declaration that God is our Provider and that we are already fully loved and supplied in Him. \'93Jireh\'94 leads the church into a place of contentment, repeating that if God clothes the lilies and watches over the sparrows, how much more will He care for His children.",\
    "theology": "Named after \'93Jehovah Jireh\'94 (Genesis 22:14), this song\'92s theology centers on God\'92s faithful provision. It echoes Jesus\'92 teaching in Matthew 6:25-34 \'96 we need not worry because our Father knows our needs. The lyrics also emphasize our identity (\'93I\'92m already loved, I\'92m already chosen\'94), reflecting Ephesians 1:4-5, that God\'92s love defines us above all. Theologically, \'93Jireh\'94 reinforces that Christ\'92s sufficiency is enough; we can be content in any circumstance because in Him we truly have all we need (Philippians 4:19, 4:11).",\
    "scripture_references": ["Matthew 6:30-33", "Genesis 22:14", "Philippians 4:19"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "\'93Jireh\'94 works well in a set when teaching on trust or following personal sharing about God\'92s provision. It\'92s a mid-tempo song with a contemplative groove \'96 allow space for the words to sink in. When leading, you might encourage the congregation between sections: for example, remind them \'93Whatever you\'92re facing, God knows and will provide.\'94 Musically, if you have multiple worship leaders, this is a great song to trade verses (as the original features male and female leads) to model unity and inclusivity. End by gently reiterating \'93You are enough\'94 to leave the congregation resting in God\'92s sufficiency.",\
    "seo_title": "Jireh \'96 Elevation & Maverick City Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Jireh\'94 by Elevation Worship & Maverick City Music is a soulful worship song about God\'92s provision and our contentment in Him. Learn about its biblical references to God as Provider, its message of identity and trust, and how to effectively lead this song in worship."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Yet Not I But Through Christ in Me",\
    "artist(s)": "CityAlight",\
    "suggested_male_key": "C",\
    "suggested_female_key": "E",\
    "tempo": "Slow",\
    "bpm": 72,\
    "themes": ["Christ\'92s strength", "grace", "perseverance"],\
    "summary": "A modern hymn that humbly acknowledges Jesus as the source of our strength, righteousness, and hope. Each verse builds on the last, reminding the congregation that from salvation to daily walk to death\'92s doorstep, it is Christ\'92s power in us that carries us through \'96 and to Him belongs all the glory.",\
    "theology": "\'93Yet Not I But Through Christ in Me\'94 is rich with Pauline theology (Galatians 2:20). It emphasizes that our lives are entirely empowered by Christ\'92s grace from start to finish. The song affirms justification (our sins forgiven through Jesus\'92 work alone), sanctification (we labor, yet His strength works mightily in us per Colossians 1:29), and glorification (the hope that He will bring us safely home \'96 Jude 24). The refrain \'93to this I hold\'94 echoes the assurance of Romans 8: that nothing can separate us from Christ. Theologically, it\'92s a declaration of total dependence on Jesus for every good thing and every victory over sin and trials.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Galatians 2:20", "2 Corinthians 12:9-10", "Colossians 1:29"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song serves well during communion or as a response to sermons about grace or reliance on God. Given its hymn-like structure, consider having the congregation read or hear the rich lyrics beforehand to fully absorb them. Musically, maintain a steady, flowing rhythm \'96 it\'92s reflective, so don\'92t rush. You might lead with simpler instrumentation (acoustic guitar or piano) to suit its contemplative nature. Encourage the church to sing out the final verse as an anthem of confidence, perhaps even dropping instruments at the line \'93when the race is complete\'94 to let voices ring a cappella in profound unity.",\
    "seo_title": "Yet Not I But Through Christ in Me \'96 CityAlight Hymn",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Yet Not I But Through Christ in Me\'94 by CityAlight is a modern hymn focusing on Christ\'92s power in the Christian life. Explore its strong theological foundation in grace and perseverance, along with practical guidance for leading this deeply meaningful song in worship."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Build Your Church",\
    "artist(s)": "Elevation Worship & Maverick City Music",\
    "suggested_male_key": "A",\
    "suggested_female_key": "D",\
    "tempo": "Medium",\
    "bpm": 89,\
    "themes": ["church", "unity", "God\'92s Kingdom"],\
    "summary": "An anthem of unity and mission that invokes Jesus\'92 promise to build His Church. It\'92s a call for God to establish His Kingdom work among us and a declaration that the Church, founded on Christ the cornerstone, will prevail against all opposition.",\
    "theology": "\'93Build Your Church\'94 is anchored in Jesus\'92 words from Matthew 16:18 that He will build His Church. Theologically, it recognizes Christ as the foundation (1 Corinthians 3:11) and affirms that we, as His people, are the living stones being built together (1 Peter 2:5). The song is both a prayer and proclamation: asking the Holy Spirit to strengthen and expand the Church, and asserting by faith that nothing can stop the advance of God\'92s Kingdom. It reinforces unity \'96 \'93we are Your Church\'94 \'96 and co-laboring with Christ in the Great Commission, relying on His power to bring growth (Acts 2:47).",\
    "scripture_references": ["Matthew 16:18", "Ephesians 2:19-20", "1 Peter 2:5"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song is powerful for services focused on church vision, unity, or missions. It has a strong, marching rhythm in 6/8 \'96 lean into that by encouraging clapping on beats or having drums drive the tempo. Invite the congregation to truly sing it as a prayer over your community and the global Church. If you have a choir or multiple vocalists, the repeating bridge (\'93Build Your church, build Your church\'85\'94) is a great moment to layer voices, symbolizing many coming together as one. Ending with an a cappella or stripped-down repeat can underscore the sincerity of our commitment to see Jesus\'92 Church thrive.",\
    "seo_title": "Build Your Church \'96 Elevation/Maverick City Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Build Your Church\'94 by Elevation Worship & Maverick City Music is a unifying worship song based on Jesus\'92 promise to establish His Church. Discover the biblical themes of unity and Kingdom mission it carries, and get tips on leading this anthem in your congregation."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Indescribable",\
    "artist(s)": "Chris Tomlin",\
    "suggested_male_key": "A",\
    "suggested_female_key": "D",\
    "tempo": "Fast",\
    "bpm": 180,\
    "themes": ["God\'92s creation", "awe", "God\'92s power"],\
    "summary": "A high-energy praise song marveling at God\'92s power in creation and His intimate care for us. \'93Indescribable\'94 rapidly lists wonders of nature \'96 from stars to lightning \'96 then humbly acknowledges that the Creator of all those also knows each of us by name, inspiring awe-filled worship.",\
    "theology": "\'93Indescribable\'94 emphasizes God\'92s transcendence and immanence. It draws on passages like Psalm 147:4 and Isaiah 40:26, which speak of God calling each star by name, to illustrate His limitless power. Simultaneously, it teaches that the almighty Creator cares personally for humanity (Matthew 6:26). Theologically, the song declares God\'92s attributes: all-powerful, all-knowing, and gracious. It leads us to confess that God is beyond full comprehension (\'93indescribable, uncontainable\'94), which is itself an act of worship acknowledging our human limitations before the infinite God (Romans 11:33).",\
    "scripture_references": ["Psalm 147:4-5", "Isaiah 40:26", "Romans 11:33"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Use \'93Indescribable\'94 as an upbeat opener or anywhere you want to lift the congregation\'92s eyes to the majesty of God. Its fast tempo (in 4/4 with a driving beat) gets people engaged \'96 encourage hand-clapping or even have the congregation sing the echo lines if appropriate. Because the verses pack in vivid imagery quickly, consider projecting visual backgrounds of stars or nature to complement the words. Remind your team to enunciate lyrics clearly so the congregation can catch the rapid descriptions. After this song, it can be impactful to transition into a quieter moment of prayer or a slower song about God\'92s love, highlighting the final lyric that this great Creator sees the depths of our hearts and still loves us.",\
    "seo_title": "Indescribable \'96 Chris Tomlin Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Indescribable\'94 by Chris Tomlin is an energetic worship song celebrating God\'92s creation and infinite power. Learn about its biblical foundation in the Psalms and Isaiah, its theme of awe and wonder, and how to lead this fast-paced song in a congregational setting."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Behold (Then Sings My Soul)",\
    "artist(s)": "Phil Wickham",\
    "suggested_male_key": "A",\
    "suggested_female_key": "D",\
    "tempo": "Medium",\
    "bpm": 74,\
    "themes": ["Christ\'92s sacrifice", "awe", "resurrection"],\
    "summary": "An awe-filled song that invites us to behold the Lamb of God on the cross and behold the empty tomb. It moves from reflective verses describing Jesus\'92 sacrifice into a soaring chorus where, like the hymn \'93How Great Thou Art,\'94 our souls sing in response to the greatness of our Savior\'92s love and victory.",\
    "theology": "\'93Behold\'94 focuses on the gospel story \'96 Jesus\'92 crucifixion and resurrection \'96 and our worshipful response. The verses draw on John 1:29 (\'93Behold the Lamb of God, who takes away the sin of the world\'94), emphasizing substitutionary atonement as Jesus dies in our place. The song then shifts to resurrection, echoing the angel\'92s words \'93Behold, He is not here \'96 He is risen\'94 (Matthew 28:6). Theologically, it melds reverence and praise: Christ\'92s suffering inspires gratitude and awe (\'93then sings my soul, how great Your love is\'94), and His triumph over death elicits triumphant worship. It reinforces that our salvation story should move our souls deeply to magnify God\'92s greatness.",\
    "scripture_references": ["John 1:29", "Isaiah 53:5", "Matthew 28:6"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "\'93Behold\'94 fits powerfully in Good Friday or Easter contexts, but also anytime the church needs to refocus on the cross. Begin the song gently and deliberately, allowing the weight of the lyrics to sink in during the verses. When the chorus arrives (\'93then sings my soul\'85\'94), invite the congregation to lift their voices strongly \'96 you can even drop instrumental volume at first to let the community hear themselves sing out, mirroring the classic hymn moment. Because it references \'93How Great Thou Art,\'94 consider tagging that hymn\'92s refrain at the end for a familiar congregational response. Close out softly with the word \'93Behold\'94 to create a moment of reflection, giving space for people to personally respond in prayer.",\
    "seo_title": "Behold (Then Sings My Soul) \'96 Phil Wickham Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Behold (Then Sings My Soul)\'94 by Phil Wickham is a worship song that reflects on Jesus\'92 crucifixion and resurrection, leading into heartfelt praise. Discover its connection to Scripture, its powerful blend of reverence and triumph, and advice for leading it in a worship setting (especially around Easter)."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Highlands (Song of Ascent)",\
    "artist(s)": "Hillsong UNITED",\
    "suggested_male_key": "G",\
    "suggested_female_key": "C",\
    "tempo": "Medium",\
    "bpm": 92,\
    "themes": ["God\'92s presence", "praise in trials", "faithfulness"],\
    "summary": "A poetic song declaring that whether we find ourselves on the mountaintop of victory or in the valley of struggle, God is equally worthy of our praise. \'93Highlands\'94 reassures the church that God\'92s grace meets us in every terrain of life and that our pursuit of Him is always met by His faithful love.",\
    "theology": "\'93Highlands\'94 is built on the truth of Psalm 139: no matter where we go \'96 heights or depths \'96 God is there. It affirms that God does not change with our circumstances; He is constant and faithful (Hebrews 13:8). The song\'92s theology encourages perseverance and constant worship: like Habakkuk 3:19, it presents God as our strength in high and low seasons alike. It also contains rich imagery of seeking God (calling Him the summit where our feet are, the valley when we\'92re low) which underlines a theology of God\'92s immanence \'96 He draws near to the brokenhearted (Psalm 34:18) and rejoices with us in victory. Ultimately, it proclaims that our response \'96 our song \'96 remains the same in every season: God be praised.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Psalm 139:7-10", "Habakkuk 3:19", "Psalm 34:18"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Due to its dynamic range, plan \'93Highlands\'94 as a journey within your set \'96 it begins reflective and builds to a passionate declaration. It\'92s excellent after a testimony or sermon about God\'92s faithfulness through hardship. When leading, be mindful of the word-dense verses; articulate clearly so people catch the poetic depth. As the song crescendos on lines like \'93no less God within the shadows,\'94 encourage the congregation to lift up those words as an offering of trust. You might prompt them, \'93Think of your own highlands or heartaches, and sing this out to God in faith.\'94 End the song softly or even a cappella to allow the profound lyrics (\'93wherever I stand, I sing through the shadows my song of ascent\'94) to linger in hearts.",\
    "seo_title": "Highlands (Song of Ascent) \'96 Hillsong UNITED",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Highlands (Song of Ascent)\'94 by Hillsong UNITED is a worship song about finding and praising God in every season \'96 from mountaintops to valleys. Learn about its scriptural inspiration, message of God\'92s unwavering presence, and tips for guiding your congregation through its powerful journey of praise."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "House of Miracles",\
    "artist(s)": "Brandon Lake",\
    "suggested_male_key": "C",\
    "suggested_female_key": "E",\
    "tempo": "Medium",\
    "bpm": 72,\
    "themes": ["Holy Spirit", "faith", "healing"],\
    "summary": "A faith-inspiring song inviting God\'92s supernatural power into our midst. It characterizes the gathering of believers (and even our own hearts) as a \'93house of miracles\'94 where Jesus is moving. The church is encouraged to surrender burdens and expectations to God, believing that in His presence, anything is possible.",\
    "theology": "\'93House of Miracles\'94 stands on the belief that God\'92s Spirit is active in His Church today (Acts 2:17-18). Theologically, it acknowledges Jesus as the ultimate authority who brings the dead to life \'96 both spiritually and physically (Ephesians 2:4-5, Mark 5:41-42). By calling the church a house of miracles, the song aligns with 1 Corinthians 3:16, reminding us that God\'92s Spirit dwells among His people. It encourages a posture of expectancy rooted in God\'92s character and promises, not hype. The lyrics submit every fear, illness, and situation to Jesus (\'93come alive in the name of Jesus\'94), reflecting the lordship of Christ over all circumstances (Philippians 2:9-10).",\
    "scripture_references": ["Acts 2:17", "Ephesians 2:4-5", "1 Corinthians 3:16"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song is effective during prayer ministry times or when stirring faith in the congregation. Consider leading it when focusing on healing, revival, or dedicating the church afresh to God. Musically, maintain a steady build; the song carries a reverent yet expectant tone. During the bridge (\'93there\'92s resurrection power\'94), encourage the church to sing boldly \'96 perhaps even speak a brief prayer like \'93Lord, we believe You\'92re working miracles now.\'94 If appropriate, you could transition into open prayer or a time of inviting people forward for prayer as the song concludes, allowing the declared faith to be exercised immediately.",\
    "seo_title": "House of Miracles \'96 Brandon Lake Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93House of Miracles\'94 by Brandon Lake is a powerful worship song inviting the Holy Spirit\'92s miraculous work in the church. Explore its emphasis on Jesus\'92 life-giving power, biblical basis for miracles today, and practical advice for incorporating this faith-building song into your worship service."\
