    "summary": "A modern hymn rejoicing that no sin or failure can exhaust God\'92s mercy. Each verse contrasts our great need with God\'92s greater compassion, leading the church to celebrate in the chorus that our sins, though many, are washed away by the infinite mercy of God through Christ.",\
    "theology": "\'93His Mercy Is More\'94 is grounded in Lamentations 3:22-23 \'96 that God\'92s mercies are new every morning and never come to an end. Theologically, it acknowledges human depravity (\'93our sins they are many\'94) while exalting divine grace (\'93His mercy is more\'94). It reflects the gospel truth that where sin increased, grace abounded all the more (Romans 5:20). The song teaches that God, rich in mercy (Ephesians 2:4), does not remember our sins against us because of Jesus\'92 atoning work. By repeatedly affirming \'93stronger than darkness, new every morn,\'94 it instills hope that each day we stand in God\'92s forgiveness. Overall, it\'92s a declaration of the doctrine of justification \'96 that we are completely forgiven and embraced by God\'92s mercy through Christ.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Lamentations 3:22-23", "Romans 5:20", "Psalm 103:12"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song serves as a joyful assurance after a time of confession or a message on grace. With its upbeat yet hymn-like feel, you can lead it with a full band or just a piano and still have impact. Teach the chorus quickly if it\'92s new \'96 it\'92s simple and repeatable. Encourage the congregation to reflect on the weight of the words \'93our sins they are many, His mercy is more\'94 \'96 even suggesting they think of specific burdens and release them to God as they sing. Musically, consider starting the first verse more reflectively and then building through the song; by the final chorus, let it ring out with thankful celebration. Tagging the last line a few extra times can foster a moment of spontaneous praise for God\'92s inexhaustible mercy.",\
