    "themes": ["God\'92s grace", "humility", "worship"],\
    "summary": "A reverent modern hymn that invites all who are weak and needy to come and worship, highlighting God\'92s welcoming grace. It portrays the contrast of our unworthiness and God\'92s goodness, leading the congregation to approach Him with humility and to be received by a kind and gracious King who deserves our highest praise.",\
    "theology": "\'93Good and Gracious King\'94 beautifully captures the gospel invitation: we come with nothing, and God welcomes us by His grace (Hebrews 4:16). Theologically, it stresses our dependency (\\"empty-handed\\") and God\'92s generosity (\\"You deserve the greater glory\\"). It echoes Jesus\'92 words, \'93Come to Me all who are weary\'94 (Matthew 11:28) and affirms justification by grace \'96 we can boldly approach the throne not because of our merit but because of Christ (Hebrews 10:19-22). The song also ascribes worth to God (\'93Holy, holy, Lord Almighty, good and gracious King\'94), aligning with biblical throne-room worship (Revelation 4:8). It teaches that God\'92s character is both sovereign (King Almighty) and merciful (good and gracious), and that understanding leads us into heartfelt, reverent praise.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Matthew 11:28", "Hebrews 4:16", "Revelation 4:8"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song fits well around communion or after a sermon on grace. Its moderate tempo and hymn-like structure mean the congregation can learn it quickly; consider teaching the chorus first. Encourage a posture of reverence \'96 perhaps invite people to bow their heads or even kneel during the early verses as a sign of humble approach. When the song shifts into the \'93Holy, holy\'94 bridge, consider raising the volume and instrumentation to emphasize the triumphant praise. If you have a larger team or choir, layering harmonies here can create a glimpse of the heavenly worship described in the lyrics. End back on a gentle note, reinforcing the personal invitation and the awe of being welcomed by our King. A short moment of silence after the song can allow individuals to personally respond in prayer or reflection.",\
    "seo_title": "Good and Gracious King \'96 CityAlight Hymn",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Good and Gracious King\'94 by CityAlight is a modern hymn about God\'92s welcoming grace and our humble worship. Explore its scriptural themes of approaching God\'92s throne freely through grace and its blend of reverence and intimacy, plus tips on leading this powerful song in your worship context."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Fear Is Not My Future",\
    "artist(s)": "Maverick City Music & Elevation Worship",\
    "suggested_male_key": "C",\
    "suggested_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo": "Medium",\
    "bpm": 69,\
    "themes": ["hope", "breakthrough", "new beginnings"],\
    "summary": "A prophetic-feeling song that encourages believers to step out of anxiety and into the hope Christ provides. It personifies fear, sickness, and heartbreak as things that don\'92t belong in our story, declaring instead that God is doing a new thing. The church is invited to say goodbye to the old (fear, sorrow) and welcome Jesus, because He is our future.",\
    "theology": "\'93Fear Is Not My Future\'94 echoes biblical assurances that in Christ, fear and death are defeated (2 Timothy 1:7, 1 Corinthians 15:55-57). Theologically, it proclaims the transformative power of Jesus: when He enters a situation, darkness gives way to light and despair to hope (John 1:5). The song\'92s bridge, repeating \'93Hello peace, hello joy, hello love...\'94, resonates with the fruit of the Spirit (Galatians 5:22-23) and the promise that God\'92s presence brings wholeness. By singing \'93fear is not my future, You are,\'94 we\'92re aligning with Jeremiah 29:11\'92s promise that God gives us a hopeful future. The song gently teaches that for the Christian, our identity and destiny are defined by Jesus\'92 lordship and goodness, not by our past traumas or current fears. Each \'93goodbye\'94 to sorrow and shame is a declaration of faith that Jesus redeems and makes all things new (Revelation 21:5).",\
    "scripture_references": ["2 Timothy 1:7", "Isaiah 43:18-19", "Revelation 21:5"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song is powerful in services focused on healing, mental health, or stepping into a new season. It has a soothing yet triumphant vibe; you might start by sharing a brief encouragement like, \'93We\'92re going to proclaim hope over our future.\'94 Encourage the congregation to sing the lyrics as declarations over their own lives (perhaps even inviting them to think of specific fears or illnesses as they sing \'93goodbye fear, goodbye grave\'94). Because the structure is call-and-response friendly, if you have worship choir or multiple leaders, use them to echo lines in the bridge, adding a communal feel. Keep instrumentation supportive and not too busy so the clear words shine. Ending the song gently by reprising \'93fear is not my future, You are\'94 a few times can allow the congregation to meditate on that truth\'97and consider opening a moment for personal prayers or ministry, as the song will likely surface areas where people need God\'92s hope.",\
    "seo_title": "Fear Is Not My Future \'96 Maverick City x Elevation Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Fear Is Not My Future\'94 by Maverick City Music & Elevation Worship is a hope-filled song about rejecting fear and embracing Jesus\'92 healing and hope. Discover its biblical foundation in promises of new beginnings, and get practical tips for leading your congregation in declaring this powerful truth."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "There Is A King",\
    "artist(s)": "Elevation Worship",\
    "suggested_male_key": "E",\
    "suggested_female_key": "A",\
    "tempo": "Slow",\
    "bpm": 64,\
    "themes": ["Jesus\'92 reign", "hope", "worship"],\
    "summary": "A reverent song that lifts eyes to Jesus enthroned above all. \'93There Is A King\'94 steadily magnifies Christ\'92s eternal reign, and promises that one day every tear and fear will be wiped away in His presence. It leads the congregation to surrender in worship now, anticipating the perfect peace of His coming Kingdom.",\
    "theology": "This song focuses on the kingship and return of Christ (Revelation 19:16, 21:4). Its theology declares Jesus as the reigning King seated among us even now (\'93where He is enthroned, there is grace\'94). It touches on inaugurated eschatology: we experience His rule in part now but await its fullness. By stating \'93every burden will be lifted... every trophy we lay down,\'94 it resonates with Philippians 2:10-11 \'96 that every knee will bow and we will cast our crowns at His feet (Revelation 4:10). The bridge\'92s hallelujahs echo the eternal worship scenes of Revelation 19. Essentially, \'93There Is A King\'94 reinforces Christ\'92s sovereignty, the hope of His second coming, and our response of awe and surrender. It assures believers that Jesus\'92 victory is certain and that the brokenness of this world will be set right under His dominion.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Revelation 21:4", "Philippians 2:10-11", "Revelation 19:6"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Use this song when you want to encourage a posture of awe and hopeful anticipation\'97perhaps after a sermon on the Kingdom of God or during communion. It has a reflective, swelling dynamic; start minimal (a single instrument or pad) to draw focus to the imagery of Jesus as King. Encourage the congregation to visualize Jesus on the throne as they sing. Through the song, gradually build volume and instrumentation to mirror the increasing exaltation in the lyrics. The repeated \'93we will watch and wait\'94 can be a moment to invite stillness\'97maybe drop instrumentation there in one repetition to let voices or silence speak. For the final chorus and spontaneous hallelujahs, let the music open up wide, inviting the church to freely express praise. Ending on a unified a cappella hallelujah can be powerful, symbolizing all voices joined for our King.",\
    "seo_title": "There Is A King \'96 Elevation Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93There Is A King\'94 by Elevation Worship is a worship song exalting Jesus\'92 reign and pointing to the hope of His coming Kingdom. Explore its scriptural themes of Christ\'92s kingship and our future hope, and get guidance on leading this inspiring anthem of surrender and praise."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Peace Be Still",\
    "artist(s)": "The Belonging Co (Hope Darst)",\
    "suggested_male_key": "F",\
    "suggested_female_key": "A",\
    "tempo": "Slow",\
    "bpm": 72,\
    "themes": ["trust", "God\'92s peace", "faith over fear"],\
    "summary": "A calming yet powerful song that encourages believers to trust Jesus in the middle of life\'92s storms. \'93Peace Be Still\'94 has a conversational tone\'97almost like a self-reminder\'97to not be afraid. It helps the congregation declare Christ\'92s authority over chaos, echoing His words to the storm, and to welcome His peace that calms our hearts.",\
    "theology": "Drawing from the gospel story of Jesus calming the storm (Mark 4:39), this song affirms that Christ has authority over nature and by extension, over every chaotic circumstance we face. The theology here is that fear is not from God (2 Timothy 1:7), and His presence brings peace (John 14:27). When the lyrics say \'93oh heart, believe,\'94 it\'92s an exhortation aligned with Psalm 27:13\'97to have faith in God\'92s goodness even when anxious. The repeated command \'93Peace, be still\'94 isn\'92t just positive thinking; it\'92s invoking the very words of Jesus, implying that through Him we can speak peace into fear. The song acknowledges our human tendency to fear but teaches us to turn our focus to the bigness of God (\'93even when my eyes can\'92t see, I will trust the voice that speaks\'94). At its core, \'93Peace Be Still\'94 is about surrendering anxiety to God and embracing the supernatural peace that transcends understanding (Philippians 4:6-7).",\
    "scripture_references": ["Mark 4:39-40", "John 14:27", "Philippians 4:6-7"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song is ideal during moments of ministry or reflection\'97like after a message on anxiety or in a prayer night. Start softly, maybe just piano and a single voice, to create a space of calm. As you lead, model the stillness: take unhurried tempos and gentle phrasing. You might encourage the congregation to inhale deeply and exhale worry as they sing the chorus, practically engaging body and spirit. If there\'92s an opportunity, have a worship leader briefly share a personal story of finding God\'92s peace to deepen the impact. Through the bridge (\'93let faith rise up\'94), gradually build intensity to help people move from a whisper of faith to a confident roar. By the end, drop back to a tender finish, almost a lullaby to the soul. Don\'92t rush out of the moment\'97perhaps let the instruments continue quietly and invite people to silently cast their cares on Jesus before moving on.",\
    "seo_title": "Peace Be Still \'96 The Belonging Co Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Peace Be Still\'94 by The Belonging Co (Hope Darst) is a worship song that speaks God\'92s peace over fear and anxiety. Learn about its foundation in Jesus calming the storm, its encouragement to trust God\'92s voice, and practical tips for leading your congregation into a place of calm and faith through this song."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "The Goodness of Jesus",\
    "artist(s)": "CityAlight",\
    "suggested_male_key": "G",\
    "suggested_female_key": "C",\
    "tempo": "Slow",\
    "bpm": 70,\
    "themes": ["rest in Christ", "satisfaction", "God\'92s goodness"],\
    "summary": "A gentle, hymn-like song inviting weary souls to find their everything in Jesus. It reassures the congregation that no burden or longing is beyond Christ\'92s care. By reflecting on His goodness and what He\'92s done for us, it encourages hearts to find true contentment and delight in the love of Jesus.",\
    "theology": "\'93The Goodness of Jesus\'94 is steeped in the idea that Jesus Himself is our rest and satisfaction (Matthew 11:28). Theologically, each verse emphasizes an aspect of Christ\'92s sufficiency: that in our weakness, His grace is enough; in our searching, He is the fulfillment. It reflects Psalm 107:9, \'93He satisfies the longing soul,\'94 and Psalm 34:8, \'93Taste and see that the Lord is good.\'94 The song fosters a personal encounter with Christ\'92s character\'97gracious, kind, faithful. It implicitly combats legalism or self-reliance by bidding us simply to \'93come\'85 and find\'94 rather than earn. By the final verse, it leads to doxology: \'93Praise the King who bore the burden,\'94 tying our experience of Jesus\'92 goodness to the gospel work of the cross. Thus, it\'92s not just therapeutic but Christ-centered, teaching that all comfort, hope, and joy flow from Jesus\'92 person and work.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Matthew 11:28", "Psalm 34:8", "Psalm 107:9"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song works beautifully during reflective moments such as after communion or in response to a sermon on God\'92s grace. Keep the arrangement simple\'97piano or acoustic guitar with light strings can carry the tender mood. Encourage the congregation to quietly meditate on the words, maybe even remaining seated to soak in the invitation. You could have different soloists sing each verse, symbolizing Jesus personally addressing various needs (weary, broken, searching), then have everyone join on the chorus. Consider projecting or speaking a short scripture between verses to reinforce the message (for example, before verse 2, quote 2 Corinthians 12:9 about His grace being sufficient). As you close, don\'92t be afraid of a moment of silence for people to pray silently, \'93Thank You, Jesus, for Your goodness in my life.\'94 The gentle nature of the song can segue into a time of prayer ministry or a quiet hymn, maintaining the atmosphere of resting in Christ\'92s goodness.",\
    "seo_title": "The Goodness of Jesus \'96 CityAlight Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93The Goodness of Jesus\'94 by CityAlight is a tender worship song inviting believers to find rest and satisfaction in Christ. Explore its rich scriptural basis about God\'92s goodness and sufficiency, and discover ways to lead this comforting song in your church\'92s worship or prayer times."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "My Worth Is Not In What I Own",\
    "artist(s)": "Keith & Kristyn Getty",\
    "suggested_male_key": "C",\
    "suggested_female_key": "E",\
    "tempo": "Medium",\
    "bpm": 65,\
    "themes": ["identity in Christ", "grace", "humility"],\
    "summary": "A modern hymn of devotion that refocuses believers on finding their value and joy in Christ alone. It rejects worldly measures of worth\'97like wealth, skill, or fame\'97and instead treasures the redemption we have through the blood of Jesus. It invites the congregation into a humble, grateful posture, boasting only in the Lord.",\
    "theology": "This song reinforces the biblical truth that our identity and worth are rooted in being redeemed by Christ (Galatians 2:20, 1 Peter 1:18-19). Theologically, it counters pride and insecurity alike by declaring that neither accomplishments nor failures define us, but rather the love and sacrifice of Jesus do. The refrain \'93I rejoice in my Redeemer, greatest treasure, wellspring of my soul\'94 echoes Philippians 3:7-8, where Paul considers all gain as loss compared to knowing Christ. The song\'92s bridge highlights the gospel paradox: life eternal through death (John 12:24-25) and that our value is firmly established by God\'92s paying price for us, not by anything inherently in us. It\'92s an anthem of Christ-esteem over self-esteem, teaching that the highest fulfillment comes from cherishing Christ above all and recognizing that in Him, we have infinite worth and security as beloved children of God (1 John 3:1).",\
    "scripture_references": ["Philippians 3:7-8", "1 Peter 1:18-19", "Jeremiah 9:23-24"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Consider using this song in services addressing identity, pride, or stewardship. Its reflective nature and moderate pace mean you should articulate lyrics clearly\'97perhaps even have the congregation read a key line with you before singing to let it sink in (e.g., \'93Two wonders here that I confess: my worth and my unworthiness\'94). Musically, a folk or acoustic approach suits it well (guitar, violin, piano). Encourage a heart-check as you introduce it: invite people to silently lay down any status or failure they\'92ve been clinging to for worth. During the final chorus, you might drop instrumentation except a simple strum or pad, allowing voices to carry the confession \'93I rejoice in my Redeemer.\'94 It could follow with a quiet prayer or lead into the classic hymn \'93When I Survey the Wondrous Cross,\'94 which resonates with similar themes of counting worldly gain as loss. Throughout, lead with humility in your tone\'97this song is as much a personal prayer as a corporate one.",\
    "seo_title": "My Worth Is Not In What I Own \'96 Getty Hymn",\
    "meta_description": "\'93My Worth Is Not In What I Own\'94 by Keith & Kristyn Getty is a modern hymn focusing on our identity in Christ rather than worldly status. Learn about its theological emphasis on redemption and grace, and find tips for leading this meaningful song to help your congregation affirm their true worth in Jesus."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Hosanna",\
    "artist(s)": "Hillsong UNITED",\
    "suggested_male_key": "C",\
    "suggested_female_key": "E",\
    "tempo": "Medium",\
    "bpm": 77,\
    "themes": ["revival", "surrender", "God\'92s glory"],\
    "summary": "A passionate worship song that blends praise with a cry for spiritual awakening. \'93Hosanna\'94 (meaning \'93save us\'94) moves from adoring Jesus as the one who is worthy and exalted, to praying for God to cleanse our hearts and send revival. The congregation is led to worship fully and also to yield themselves as agents of God\'92s Kingdom coming on earth.",\
    "theology": "The song\'92s chorus \'93Hosanna in the highest\'94 is the praise given to Jesus during the triumphal entry (Matthew 21:9), acknowledging Him as Messiah and King. Its theology encompasses both worship and mission: recognizing God\'92s glory filling the earth (Isaiah 6:3) and desiring personal purification (\'93break my heart for what breaks Yours\'94 echoes Nehemiah 1:4 and Ephesians 4:32 in compassion). The bridge is a prayer of consecration and revival, aligning with 2 Chronicles 7:14 \'96 asking God to heal our land as we turn to Him. \'93Hosanna\'94 teaches that true worship not only exalts Jesus but also changes us, stirring us to love others and seek God\'92s renewing work in our generation. It holds an eschatological hope too: as we sing \'93I see the King of glory coming,\'94 we anticipate Jesus\'92 return and the ultimate revival of all things under His reign.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Matthew 21:9", "Isaiah 6:3", "2 Chronicles 7:14"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song works powerfully in youth services, prayer gatherings, or any setting longing for God\'92s move. Its verses are contemplative and its bridge builds to high intensity\'97plan your dynamics accordingly. In the early verses, perhaps have just one voice leading to create intimacy, then invite full band and vocals by the time the chorus hits. Encourage the congregation not just to sing but to pray the bridge: you might say, \'93As we sing these next lines, make them your personal prayer.\'94 If possible, flow from the bridge into spontaneous prayer or a continued vamp where people can voice short prayers for revival, justice, or personal surrender. The final chorus after such a moment often erupts with fresh meaning. Instrumentally, let the drums and electric guitar drive the swell on the bridge \'93Heal my heart and make it clean\'85,\'94 and consider pulling back at \'93as I walk from earth into eternity\'94 to a softer dynamic, ending on a note of reverent expectation. This ebb and flow mirrors the song\'92s blend of awe and earnest petition.",\
    "seo_title": "Hosanna \'96 Hillsong UNITED Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Hosanna\'94 by Hillsong UNITED is a worship song blending praise with a prayer for revival and personal transformation. Explore its biblical references (from Jesus\'92 triumphal entry to themes of heart-change) and get practical advice for leading this impactful song, guiding your congregation in both exaltation and surrender."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "The More I Seek You",\
    "artist(s)": "Gateway Worship (Kari Jobe)",\
    "suggested_male_key": "C",\
    "suggested_female_key": "E",\
    "tempo": "Slow",\
    "bpm": 86,\
    "themes": ["intimacy with God", "love of God", "rest"],\
    "summary": "A tender, intimate worship song that expresses a deep longing to be close to Jesus. Its lyrics use the imagery of sitting at Jesus\'92 feet, drinking from His cup, and leaning against Him\'97conveying a childlike trust and contentment in God\'92s presence. It invites the congregation into a personal moment of adoration and rest in God\'92s love.",\
    "theology": "This song reflects the heart of Mary of Bethany (Luke 10:39) who sat at Jesus\'92 feet, prioritizing closeness to Him. Theologically, it emphasizes God\'92s love and our response of devotion (1 John 4:19). Phrases like \'93laying back against You and breathing\'94 highlight God\'92s nearness and the Holy Spirit\'92s comfort (John 13:23 suggests John leaning on Jesus at the Last Supper\'97a posture of intimacy). The song\'92s core truth is that as we seek God more, we experience more of His sweetness and peace (Psalm 63:1-5). It\'92s not heavy on propositional doctrine but rich in experiential theology: that knowing God\'92s heart of love surpasses knowledge (Ephesians 3:17-19). By repeating \'93I want to sit at Your feet,\'94 it subtly teaches that our highest calling and satisfaction come from worship and communion with God, not from doing things for Him. It is essentially a love song to Jesus that reinforces the relational aspect of our faith.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Luke 10:39", "Psalm 63:1", "Ephesians 3:17-19"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Because of its intimate nature, this song often works best in slower, prayerful parts of a service\'97perhaps after communion or during an extended worship night. Encourage the congregation to close their eyes or even find a posture of rest (sitting or kneeling) to fully engage with the imagery. Minimal instrumentation is key; a soft keyboard pad or acoustic guitar picking can suffice. Don\'92t rush\'97allow for space between lines or repeats for reflection. You might gently prompt people, saying, \'93Feel free to sing these words directly to Jesus like it\'92s just you and Him here.\'94 If spontaneous expressions of love for God arise, nurture that\'97maybe hold a chord and invite people to whisper their own simple prayer (\'93I love You, Lord\'94). End softly; perhaps transition into silence or a very familiar chorus like \'93I Love You, Lord\'94 to continue the theme without jarring the atmosphere. The goal is to help people personally encounter God\'92s presence, so maintain a shepherding sensitivity\'97less is more when guiding a moment as intimate as this.",\
    "seo_title": "The More I Seek You \'96 Gateway Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93The More I Seek You\'94 by Gateway Worship (Kari Jobe) is a gentle worship song about intimate communion with God. Discover how it draws from biblical moments of closeness to God, and get tips for leading your congregation into a personal, restful encounter with Jesus through this song."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Refiner's Fire",\
    "artist(s)": "Brian Doerksen",\
    "suggested_male_key": "D",\
    "suggested_female_key": "G",\
    "tempo": "Slow",\
    "bpm": 75,\
    "themes": ["purification", "holiness", "surrender"],\
    "summary": "A classic worship chorus that serves as a heartfelt prayer for God to purify and refine our hearts. \'93Refiner\'92s Fire\'94 gently leads the congregation in asking God to cleanse them from sin and set their hearts apart for Him. With simple, earnest lyrics, it expresses our desire to be holy and pleasing to the Lord, refined like pure gold.",\
    "theology": "This song is based on the biblical imagery of God as a refiner of His people (Malachi 3:2-3). Theologically, it acknowledges sanctification\'97the process by which God purges impurity from our lives so that we reflect His character more fully (1 Peter 1:6-7). The line \'93My heart\'92s one desire is to be holy\'94 echoes Scriptures like Psalm 51:10 (\'93create in me a clean heart\'94) and 1 Peter 1:15-16 (be holy as God is holy). By calling God the \'93Refiner\'92s fire,\'94 it recognizes that trials and divine discipline can be used to remove dross and increase our faith\'92s genuineness. It\'92s a humble song of surrender: we present ourselves for God\'92s testing and purifying, trusting His flame not to destroy but to purify (Job 23:10). Ultimately, it teaches that holiness is not self-produced but is a work of God in which we cooperate by yielding ourselves to His flame, longing to come forth as pure gold for His glory.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Malachi 3:2-3", "Psalm 51:10", "1 Peter 1:6-7"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "\'93Refiner\'92s Fire\'94 often fits well after a sermon on holiness or as part of a consecration moment (like the close of a retreat or beginning of a new year). Since it\'92s familiar to many, you can encourage those who know it to close their eyes and sing from memory, really making it a prayer. Lead with gentle conviction\'97perhaps sharing a brief personal word on what the song means to you. Musically, it works beautifully with just keys or guitar and light backing vocals; focus on dynamics by possibly dropping instruments during \'93purify my heart\'94 sections to highlight those pleas. Allow a short instrumental between repeats where people can personally talk to God, confessing or inviting His refining work. You might segue from this into a time of silence or an altar call for those who want to symbolically step forward as a sign of surrendering to God\'92s purification. Keep the atmosphere reflective and reverent, and conclude with reassurance\'97maybe quote 1 John 1:9\'97that as we confess and seek holiness, He is faithful to cleanse us, leaving the congregation both challenged and comforted in God\'92s grace.",\
    "seo_title": "Refiner's Fire \'96 Brian Doerksen Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Refiner\'92s Fire\'94 by Brian Doerksen is a well-loved worship song asking God to purify our hearts. Learn about its biblical basis in God\'92s refining process and holiness, and find guidance on leading this song in a prayerful, surrender-filled moment of worship."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Days of Elijah",\
    "artist(s)": "Robin Mark",\
    "suggested_male_key": "Bb",\
    "suggested_female_key": "D",\
    "tempo": "Fast",\
    "bpm": 101,\
    "themes": ["revival", "second coming", "righteousness"],\
    "summary": "An upbeat, declarative song that celebrates God\'92s work in tumultuous times, using prophetic imagery from the Bible. It rallies the church with lyrics about being a voice of righteousness like Elijah, a servant of worship like David, and anticipating the coming of the Lord. \'93Days of Elijah\'94 stirs excitement and unity as the congregation proclaims, \'93Behold He comes, riding on the clouds!\'94",\
    "theology": "\'93Days of Elijah\'94 strings together biblical allusions to communicate that God is moving in our present day as He did in the past. It mentions Elijah (1 Kings 18) to symbolize a call back to God during apostasy, Moses (righteousness being restored, akin to receiving the Law), and David (rebuilding worship, referencing Amos 9:11). Theologically, it affirms that despite trials (\'93though these are days of great trial\'94), the harvest is ready (Matthew 9:37) and God\'92s purposes will stand. The climactic line \'93Behold He comes\'94 echoes the promise of Jesus\'92 return (Revelation 1:7) and foreshadows the ultimate victory and reign of Christ. Declaring \'93there\'92s no god like Jehovah\'94 reinforces monotheism and God\'92s unmatched power (Isaiah 45:5). In sum, the song encourages hope, holy living, and evangelistic zeal, rooted in the belief that we live in significant times where God\'92s hand is at work and Jesus\'92 return draws near. It's a call to prepare the way of the Lord (Isaiah 40:3) by being faithful witnesses now.",\
    "scripture_references": ["1 Kings 18:21", "Matthew 24:30", "Revelation 1:7"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song\'92s energy and message make it ideal for openers or closing an upbeat service, especially around themes of revival or Christ\'92s return. Invite clapping from the first beat, and consider using a drummer to kick off the driving rhythm. The call-and-response \'93there\'92s no god like Jehovah\'94 bridge is a great chance to involve the congregation actively\'97maybe split the room or echo with a choir if you have one. Because the lyrics pack a lot of imagery, consider briefly explaining the heart of the song before singing (e.g., \'93We\'92re about to sing about being like Elijah and Moses\'97not literally, but standing for God and righteousness today!\'94). A tambourine or even some synchronized movement can add to the celebratory feel. If appropriate in your context, you might even encourage a shout of \'93lift your voice!\'94 or a literal shout of praise on the final chorus to engage folks fully. End big\'97perhaps repeating the final line \'93Behold He comes\'85\'94 one more time a cappella or with a loud final chord to drive home the triumphant note. This song leaves people encouraged and stirred, so ride that momentum into a victory shout or a confident closing prayer.",\
    "seo_title": "Days of Elijah \'96 Robin Mark Worship Song",\
    "meta_description": "\'93Days of Elijah\'94 by Robin Mark is a rousing worship song referencing biblical figures and themes of revival and Christ\'92s return. Discover the meaning behind its prophetic imagery, the scriptural promises it celebrates, and tips on leading this high-energy anthem to inspire hope and action in your congregation."\
  \},\
  \{\
    "title": "Joy of the Lord",\
    "artist(s)": "Rend Collective",\
    "suggested_male_key": "C",\
    "suggested_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo": "Fast",\
    "bpm": 99,\
    "themes": ["joy", "strength in God", "perseverance"],\
    "summary": "An upbeat, folk-infused song that encourages rejoicing in God even in the midst of hardship. It boldly declares that the joy of the Lord is our strength, prompting the congregation to choose praise over despair. With its catchy melody and clapping rhythm, it injects hope and celebration, reminding everyone that because God is with us, we can face anything with joy.",\
    "theology": "The central scripture of this song is Nehemiah 8:10, \'93the joy of the Lord is your strength.\'94 Theologically, it acknowledges that trials and darkness are real (\'93Though tears may fall, my song will rise\'94), but asserts a response of faith \'96 much like Habakkuk 3:17-18, choosing to rejoice in God regardless of circumstances. It teaches that joy is a fruit of the Spirit and a decision empowered by knowing God\'92s character and promises (Psalm 28:7). The song also implies the doctrine of God\'92s immanence: He is present in our midnight hour, thus we can praise (Acts 16:25). Declaring \'93I will shout... you are the strength of my life\'94 is a statement of reliance on God (Psalm 27:1). Overall, it\'92s a musical embodiment of Philippians 4:4, encouraging constant rejoicing in the Lord. The repeated refrain instills that our gladness isn\'92t based on fleeting situations but on the Lord\'92s unchanging goodness and might that uplifts us when we are weak.",\
    "scripture_references": ["Nehemiah 8:10", "Habakkuk 3:17-18", "Psalm 28:7"],\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This song shines as a service opener or anywhere you want to lift the congregation\'92s spirit. Its folksy, foot-stomping vibe means you can have fun with instrumentation: add a banjo, mandolin, or just ensure a strong acoustic guitar strum and a beat (even a kick drum or floor tom can drive it). Teach the chorus quickly if people are new to it, possibly by echo. Encourage physical expression \'96 clapping, bouncing, even dancing if your church is open to it! Between sections, a quick exhortation like \'93Let\'92s choose joy together!\'94 can galvanize participation. Use dynamics: maybe drop instruments on an early chorus to let handclaps and voices carry, then slam back in with full sound. The bridge (\'93when sorrow comes...\'94) builds anticipation \'96 you could split the singing between men and women or halves of the room to keep engagement high. Finish strong and repetitive, perhaps extending the final \'93joy of the Lord is my strength\'94 refrain with extra enthusiasm. Ending on a sustained upbeat chord with everyone clapping or cheering can segue wonderfully into a greeting time or next song, riding the wave of joy you've just cultivated in the room.",\
